<subsection xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"><title> Separation of Variables (SOV) Method </title>

	<introduction>

		<p>
			The <em>separation of variables</em> method is a cornerstone technique for solving first-order differential equations. This method works when the equation is <xref ref="separable" text="custom">separable</xref>, meaning it can be rearranged to isolate all terms involving the dependent variable (<m>y</m>) on one side and all terms involving the independent variable (<m>x</m>) on the other. While identifying a first-order equation is straightforward (it involves a first derivative and no higher derivatives), determining if it's separable may require some algebraic manipulation.
		</p>

	</introduction>

	<subsubsection><title> SOV Method Steps </title>

		<exploration xml:id="sov-method"><title> Separation of Variables (SOV) </title>
		
			<p>
				If a differential equation can be written in the separable form
				<me xml:id="sov-method-de">
					\frac{dy}{dx} = f(x) \cdot g(y)
				</me>,
				then the general solution can be determined through the steps below.
			</p>

			<dl>

				<li xml:id="sov-step-1"><title> Step 1: Separate Variables </title>
					<p>
						Rearrange the equation so that all terms involving the dependent variable <m>y</m> are on one side, and all terms involving the independent variable <m>x</m> are on the other:
						<me>
							\frac{1}{g(y)}\ dy = f(x)\ dx
						</me>.
					</p>
				</li>
				
				<li xml:id="sov-step-2"><title> Step 2: Integrate Both Sides </title>
					<p>
						Integrate both sides of the equation with respect to their respective variables:
						<me>
							\int \frac{1}{g(y)}\ dy = \int f(x) \ dx
						</me>.
					</p>
				</li>

				<li xml:id="sov-step-3"><title> Step 3: Isolate the Solution </title>
					<p>
						Isolate <m>y</m> to obtain the general solution. If it is not possible to explicitly solve for <m>y</m>, leave the solution in its implicit form.
					</p>
				</li>

			</dl>

		</exploration>
		
		<identity xml:id="treating-dydx-as-a-fraction"><title> Treating <m>\frac{dy}{dx}</m> as a Fraction </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Since the derivative resembles a fraction, a common practice is to treat the derivative as the divison of <m>dy</m> by <m>dx</m>. This violation often works and can simplify the math as it did in the SOV method, where we write the DE as
					<me>
						\frac{1}{g(y)}\ dy = f(x)\ dx
					</me>
					before integrating the left with respect to <m>y</m> and the right with respect to <m>x</m>. However, integrating both sides of an equation with respect to different variables is another violation that still happens to work in this case. To see this, consider a more proper approach where we rewrite the equation as
					<me>
						\frac{1}{g(y)}\frac{dy}{dx} = f(x)
					</me>
					and then integrate both sides with respect to <m>x</m>, giving
					<md>
						<mrow> \int \frac{1}{g(y(x))} \ob{\frac{dy}{dx}\ dx}^{dy} =\amp\ \int f(x)\ dx</mrow>
						<mrow> \int \frac{1}{g(y)} \ dy =\amp\ \int f(x)\ dx</mrow>
					</md>,
					which is the same integral you see in the <xref ref="sov-step-2" text="custom">integration step</xref>. A keen eye may even recognize this last step as <m>u</m>-substitution from calculus.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</identity>

		<p>
			This method is a powerful tool for solving many first-order differential equations and is a great starting point for learning how to solve differential equations. It is also unique in that it can handle non-linear equations, which are often more challenging to solve.
		</p>

		<p>
			While the steps of this method are fairly straightforward, the real challenge for most students will come from the algebra and integration techniques required in each step. Use these examples not only to learn this method, but also as an opportunity to sharpen your algebra skills. With that said, let's dive into a series of examples to help you start tackling problems on your own.
		</p>

		<assemblage>
			<p>
				<xi:include href="./chkpts-2-1-sov-method-steps.ptx" />
			</p>
		</assemblage>

	</subsubsection>

	<subsubsection><title> SOV Examples </title>

		<p>
			These examples provide a step-by-step application of the separation of variables (SOV) method. They progress from basic to more advanced problems, helping you build a strong foundation while exploring more complex cases.
		</p>

		<p>
			For now, focus on following the general steps of the SOV method and gaining familiarity with the process. Later examples will introduce more advanced algebraic and integration techniques.
		</p>

		<example xml:id="sov-method-basic-examples">

			<statement>

				<p>
					Find the general solution to the following differential equations using the separation of variables method.
				</p>

				<p>
					<me>
						1.\quad \frac{dy}{dx} = x^2, \qquad 
						2.\quad \frac{dy}{dx} = y^2, \qquad 
						3.\quad \frac{dy}{dx} + \frac{x}{y^2} = 0
					</me>
				</p>

			</statement>

			<solution>

				<p>
					Although <xref ref="direct-integration" text="title"/> can be used to solve this equation, so can separation of variables, so let's apply it instead.
				</p>
	
				<p>
					The equation has order 1 and rewriting it as
					<me>
						\frac{dy}{dx} = 
						\underset{f(x)}{\underset{\uparrow}{\textcolor{BurntOrange}{\big( x^2 \big)}}} \cdot 
						\underset{g(y)}{\underset{\uparrow}{\textcolor{SeaGreen}{\big( 1 \big)}}}
					</me>
					shows that it is separable, so, we apply the SOV method as follows:
				</p>
		
				<p>
					Step 1: <xref ref="sov-step-1" text="title" /> all the dependent, <m>y</m>, terms on the left and all independent variable, <m>x</m>, terms on the right, giving
				</p>

				<p>
					<me>
						\frac{1}{\textcolor{SeaGreen}{( 1 )}} dy = \textcolor{BurntOrange}{( x^2 )} \ dx
					</me>
				</p>
		
				<p>
					Step 2: <xref ref="sov-step-2" text="title" /> both sides with respect to <m>x</m>, like so
				</p>

				<p>
					<md>
						<mrow> \int 1\ dy \amp = \int x^2\ dx</mrow>
						<mrow> y + c_1	\amp = \frac13 x^3 + c_2. </mrow>
					</md>
				</p>
	
				<p>
					Step 3: <xref ref="sov-step-3" text="title" /> <m>y</m>, remembering to combine constants.
				</p>

				<p>
					<md>
						<mrow> y =\amp\ \frac13 x^3 + c_2 - c_1	</mrow>
						<mrow> y =\amp \frac13 x^3 + c			</mrow>
					</md>
				</p>

			</solution>

			<solution>

				<p>
					The differential equation has order 1 and is separable since
					<me>
						\frac{dy}{dx} = 
						\underset{f(x)}{\underset{\uparrow}{\textcolor{BurntOrange}{\big( 1 \big)}}} \cdot 
						\underset{g(y)}{\underset{\uparrow}{\textcolor{SeaGreen}{\big( y^2 \big)}}}
					</me>
				</p>
		
				<p>
					Step 1: <xref ref="sov-step-1" text="title" /> all the dependent, <m>y</m>, terms on the left and all independent variable, <m>x</m>, terms on the right,
				</p>

				<p>
					<me>
						\frac{1}{\textcolor{SeaGreen}{( y^2 )}} dy = \textcolor{BurntOrange}{( 1 )} \ dx
					</me>.
				</p>
		
				<p>
					Step 2: <xref ref="sov-step-2" text="title" /> both sides with respect to <m>x</m>, like so
				</p>

				<p>
					<md>
						<mrow> \int y^{-2}\ dy \amp = \int 1\ dx</mrow>
						<mrow> \frac{y^{-1}}{-1} + c_1	\amp = x + c_2. </mrow>
					</md>
				</p>
	
				<p>
					Step 3: <xref ref="sov-step-3" text="title" /> <m>y</m>, remembering to combine constants.
				</p>

				<p>
					<md>
						<mrow>  -\frac{1}{y}	\amp = x + c_2 - c_1	</mrow>
						<mrow>  \frac{1}{y}		\amp = -x + c \quad \leftarrow \text{combined constant} </mrow>
						<mrow>  			y	\amp = \frac{1}{-x + c}	</mrow>
					</md>
				</p>
			</solution>

			<solution>

				<p>
					The equation is first-order and separable since
					<me>
						\frac{dy}{dx} = - \frac{x}{y} = 
						\textcolor{BurntOrange}{\left( -x \right)} \cdot 
						\textcolor{SeaGreen}{\left( \frac{1}{y^2} \right)}
					</me>
				</p>
		
				<sidebyside widths="36% 64%" valigns="top top">
					
					<p>
						Separate <m>\rightarrow</m>
					</p>

					<p>
						<me>
							\textcolor{SeaGreen}{y^2}\ dy = \textcolor{BurntOrange}{-x}\ dx
						</me>
					</p>

				</sidebyside>

				<sidebyside widths="36% 64%" valigns="top top">
				
					<p>
						Integrate <m>\rightarrow</m>
					</p>

					<p>
						<md>
							<mrow>			\int y^2\ dy 	\amp = \int -x\ dx				</mrow>
							<mrow>	\frac{y^{3}}{3} + c_1	\amp = -\frac{x^{2}}{2} + c_2.	</mrow>
						</md>
					</p>

				</sidebyside>

				<sidebyside widths="36% 64%" valigns="top top">
				
					<p>
						Isolate <m>\rightarrow</m>
					</p>

					<p>
						<md>
							<mrow> 	\frac{y^{3}}{3}	\amp = -\frac{x^{2}}{2} + \underset{=\ c_3}{\underbrace{c_2 - c_1}}  		</mrow>
							<mrow>  		y^{3}	\amp = -3\cdot\frac{x^{2}}{2} + \underset{=\ c}{\underbrace{3\cdot c_3}} 	</mrow>
							<mrow>  		y^{3}	\amp = -\frac32 x^2 + c 													</mrow>
						</md>
					</p>

				</sidebyside>

				<sidebyside widths="36% 64%" valigns="middle middle">
				
					<p>
						General Solution <m>\rightarrow</m>
					</p>

					<p>
						<md>
							<mrow> y \amp = \left(-\frac32 x^2 + c \right)^{1/3} </mrow>
						</md>
					</p>

				</sidebyside>
	
			</solution>

		</example>

		<p>
			The next collection of problems go beyond the basics and require more advanced algebraic manipulations or integration techniques to solve. Each example will deepen your understanding of the separation of variables method (SOV) and its application to more complex differential equations.
		</p>

		<example>

			<statement>
				<p>
					Solve the differential equations using the SOV method.
				</p>

				<p>
					<me>
						1.\quad \frac{dy}{dx} = \frac{\cos x}{y}, \qquad\qquad
						2.\quad y^2 y' - 1 = 6x^2.
					</me>
				</p>

			</statement>
			
			<solution>

				<p>
					The equation is separable since it can be written as:
					<me>\ds  \frac{dy}{dx} = \big( \cos x \big) \cdot \left( \frac{1}{y} \right).</me>
					Now we apply the separation of variables method.
				</p>

				<p>
					<sidebyside widths="36% 64%" valigns="middle middle">
						
						<p>
							Separate <m>\rightarrow</m>
						</p>

						<p>
							<md>
								<mrow> y\ dy				=\amp\ \cos(x)\ dx			  </mrow>
							</md>
						</p>

					</sidebyside>
				</p>

				<p>
					<sidebyside widths="36% 64%" valigns="top middle">
						
						<p>
							Integrate <m>\rightarrow</m>
						</p>

						<p>
							<md>
								<mrow> 			\int y\ dy	=\amp\ \int \cos(x)\ dx	</mrow>
								<mrow>	\frac{y^2}{2} + c_1	=\amp\ \sin(x) + c_2	</mrow>
							</md>
						</p>

					</sidebyside>
				</p>

				<p>

					<sidebyside widths="36% 64%" valigns="top top">
						
						<p>
							Isolate <m>\rightarrow</m>
						</p>

						<p>
							<md>
								<mrow>	\frac{y^2}{2}	=\amp\ \sin(x) + \os{\large c}{\boxed{c_2-c_1}}	</mrow>
								<mrow>				y^2	=\amp\ 2\sin(x) + 2c							</mrow>
							</md>
						</p>

					</sidebyside>

				</p>

				<p>
					
					<sidebyside widths="36% 64%" valigns="middle middle">
						<p>
							General Solution <m>\rightarrow</m>
						</p>
						<p>
							<md>
								<mrow>	y(x)	=\amp\ \pm\sqrt{2\sin(x) + c}	</mrow>
							</md>.
						</p>
					</sidebyside>

				</p>

				<p>
					Before moving on, let's address a few things about this solution.	
					<dl>
						<li><title> <em>A Common Error</em> </title>
							<p>
								A common algebra error is to further simplify the solution, as follows
								<md>
									<mrow>	y(x)	=\amp\ \pm\sqrt{2\sin(x)} + \sqrt{c}	\quad \leftarrow \text{Common Error}		</mrow>
									<mrow>	y(x)	=\amp\ \pm\sqrt{2\sin(x)} + c			\quad \leftarrow \text{Incorrect Solution}	</mrow>
								</md>.
							</p>
						</li>
						<li><title> <em>The <m>\pm</m> Sign</em> </title>
							<p>
								The <m>\pm</m> symbol in the general solution is required since both the positive and negative versions of this function are solutions. The sign becomes more important when we are seeking a particular solution. 
							</p>
						</li>
					</dl>
				</p>

			</solution>

			<solution>

				<p>
					This differential equation is separable as it can be written as:
					<md>
						<mrow> y^2 y' - 1 =\amp\ 6x^2														</mrow>
						<mrow> y' =\amp\ \frac{6x^2 + 1}{y^2}												</mrow>
						<mrow> \frac{dy}{dx} =\amp\ \big( 6x^2 + 1 \big)\cdot \left( \frac{1}{y^2} \right)	</mrow>
					</md>
					Therefore, we can apply the separation of variables method.
				</p>

				<p>
					<sidebyside widths="36% 64%" valigns="middle middle">
						
						<p>
							Separate <m>\rightarrow</m>
						</p>

						<p>
							<md>
								<mrow>	y^2\ dy	=\amp\ (6x^2+1)\ dx	</mrow>
							</md>
						</p>

					</sidebyside>
				</p>

				<p>
					<sidebyside widths="36% 64%" valigns="middle middle">
						
						<p>
							Integrate <m>\rightarrow</m>
						</p>

						<p>
							<md>
								<mrow>	\int y^2\ dy	=\amp\ \int (6x^2+1)\ dx	</mrow>
							</md>
						</p>

					</sidebyside>
				</p>

				<p>
					<sidebyside widths="36% 64%" valigns="top top">
						
						<p>
							Isolate <m>\rightarrow</m>
						</p>

						<p>
							<md>
								<mrow>	\frac{y^3}{3} + c_1	=\amp\ 2x^3 + x + c_2								</mrow>
								<mrow>	\frac{y^3}{3}		=\amp\ 2x^3 + x + \os{\large c}{\boxed{c_2-c_1}}	</mrow>
								<mrow>	y^3					=\amp\ 6x^3 + 3x + 3c								</mrow>
							</md>
						</p>

					</sidebyside>
				</p>

				<p>
					
					<sidebyside widths="36% 64%" valigns="middle middle">
						<p>
							General Solution <m>\rightarrow</m>
						</p>
						<p>
							<md>
								<mrow> y					=\amp\ \sqrt[3]{6x^3 + 3x + c}						</mrow>
							</md>.
						</p>
					</sidebyside>

				</p>

			</solution>

		</example>

		<p>
			Now let's use the separation of variables method to solve a few initial-value problems. These problems require finding a particular solution that satisfies a given initial condition.
		</p>

		<example>

			<statement>
				<p>
					Find the particular solution to the initial-value problem
					<me>
						\frac{dy}{dx} = \frac{\cos x}{y}, \quad y(0) = -5
					</me>
				</p>
			</statement>

			<solution>
				<p>
					From previous example, the general solution is
					<me>
						y(x) = \pm\sqrt{2\sin(x) + c}.
					</me>
					where the <m>\pm</m> sign means that the general solution includes both the positive and negative square roots. However, when finding a particular solution, only one applies. In this case, the initial condition <m>y(0) = -5</m> indicates that <m>y</m> is negative when <m>x = 0</m>. Therefore, the particular solution must come from the form containing the negative sign. Substituting the initial condition:
					<md>
						<mrow>	-5	=\amp\ -\sqrt{2\sin(0) + c} = -\sqrt{0 + c} = -\sqrt{c}	</mrow>
						<mrow>	5	=\amp\ \sqrt{c} \quad \implies \quad c = 25				</mrow>
					</md>
					Therefore, the solution to the initial-value problem is:
					<me>
						y(x) = -\sqrt{2\sin(x) + 25}
					</me>
				</p>
			</solution>

		</example>

		<example>

			<statement>
				<p>
					Find the particular solution to the initial-value problem
					<me>
						z' - 1 = z^2, \quad z(4) = 9
					</me>
				</p>
			</statement>

			<solution>

				<p>
					This differential equation is first order and separable since
					<md>
						<mrow> z' - 1 =\amp\ z^2							</mrow>
						<mrow> z' =\amp\ z^2 + 1							</mrow>
						<mrow> z' =\amp\ \big( 1 \big) \big( z^2 + 1 \big)  </mrow>
					</md>
					Therefore, we can apply the separation of variables method.
				</p>

				<p>
					<sidebyside widths="36% 64%" valigns="middle middle">
						
						<p>
							Separate <m>\rightarrow</m>
						</p>

						<p>
							<md>
								<mrow>	\frac{1}{z^2+1}dz	=\amp\ 1\ dt	</mrow>
							</md>
						</p>

					</sidebyside>
				</p>

				<p>
					<sidebyside widths="36% 64%" valigns="top middle">
						
						<p>
							Integrate <m>\rightarrow</m>
						</p>

						<p>
							<md>
								<mrow>	\int\frac{1}{z^2+1}\ dz	=\amp\ \int 1\ dt	</mrow>
								<mrow>			\arctan z + c_1	=\amp\ t + c_2		</mrow>
							</md>
						</p>

					</sidebyside>
				</p>

				<p>
					<sidebyside widths="36% 64%" valigns="middle middle">
						
						<p>
							Isolate <m>\rightarrow</m>
						</p>

						<p>
							<md>
								<mrow>	\arctan z	=\amp\ t + \boxed{c_2-c_1}	</mrow>
							</md>
						</p>

					</sidebyside>
				</p>

				<p>
					<sidebyside widths="36% 64%" valigns="middle middle">
						
						<p>
							General Solution <m>\rightarrow</m>
						</p>

						<p>
							<md>
								<mrow>	z	=\amp\ \tan(t+c) \quad \left( c = c_2 - c_1 \right)	</mrow>	
							</md>.
						</p>

					</sidebyside>
				</p>


				<p>
					Substituting, <m>z(4) = 9</m>, into the general solution, we get
					<md>
						<mrow>	9 = \tan(4+c) \implies	\amp\ \tan^{-1}(9) = 4 + c	</mrow>
						<mrow>							\amp\ \tan^{-1}(9) - 4 = c	</mrow>
					</md>
					Therefore, the solution to the intial-valued problem is
					<aside>
						<p>
							Note, if you approximate <m>c</m> (e.g. <m>-2.54</m>), the solution
							<me>
								z = \tan(t - 2.54)
							</me>,
							no longer satisfies the initial condition <m>z(4) = 9</m>.
						</p>
					</aside>
					<me>
						z = \tan(t + \tan^{-1}(9) - 4)
					</me>
					
				</p>
			</solution>

		</example>

		<p>
			In the previous examples, we were able to explicitly solve for the dependent variable in terms of the independent variable. However, in some cases, we may only be able to provide an implicit solution, as shown in the next example.
		</p>
		
		<example>

			<p>
				Solve the initial-value problem
				<me> 
					Q Q' + e^Q Q' = t, \quad Q(0) = 0
				</me>
			</p>
		
			<solution>

				<p>
					Since all the <m>Q</m> terms are on the left and all the <m>t</m> terms are on the right, we can just factor out <m>Q'</m> on the left to separate the equation.
				</p>

				<p>
					<sidebyside widths="36% 64%" valigns="middle middle">
						
						<p>
							Separate <m>\rightarrow</m>
						</p>

						<p>
							<md>
								<mrow>	\left(Q + e^Q\right)dQ	=\amp\ tdt	</mrow>
							</md>
						</p>

					</sidebyside>
				</p>

				<p>
					<sidebyside widths="36% 64%" valigns="top middle">
						
						<p>
							Integrate <m>\rightarrow</m>
						</p>

						<p>
							<md>
								<mrow>	\int \left(Q + e^Q\right)dQ	=\amp\ \int t\ dt	</mrow>
								<mrow>	\frac12 Q^2 + e^Q	=\amp\ \frac{1}{2}t^2 + c_1			</mrow>
							</md>
						</p>

					</sidebyside>
				</p>

				<p>
					<sidebyside widths="36% 64%" valigns="middle middle">
						
						<p>
							Isolate <m>\rightarrow</m>
						</p>

						<p>
							<md>
								<mrow>			Q^2 + 2e^Q	=\amp\ t^2 + \us{c}{\boxed{2c_1}}	</mrow>.
							</md>
						</p>

					</sidebyside>
				</p>

				<p>
					<sidebyside widths="36% 64%" valigns="middle middle">
						
						<p>
							General Solution <m>\rightarrow</m>
						</p>

						<p>
							<md>
								<mrow>	Q^2 + 2e^Q = t^2 + c	</mrow>.
							</md>.
						</p>

					</sidebyside>
				</p>

				<p>
					Note that there is no nice way to find <m>Q</m> explicitly. In these cases, it is ok to leave the general solution in this implicit form. We can still find <m>c</m> using initial condition. Recall, that <m>Q(0) = 0</m> means that when <m>t = 0</m>, <m>Q = 0</m>. Substituting these values in, we get
					<md>
						<mrow>	0^2 + 2e^0	=\amp\ 0^2 + c	</mrow>
						<mrow>			2	=\amp\ c		</mrow>
					</md>
					Therefore, the solution to the initial-valued problem is
					<me> 
						Q^2 + 2e^Q = t^2 + 2
					</me>.
				</p>

			</solution>
		
		</example>

		<p>
			This example illustrates strategies for combining constants and dealing with absolute values that often arise when solving differential equations.
		</p>

		<example>
			
			<p>
				Find the general solution to the differential equation
				<me>
					x\frac{dy}{dx} + 10x^2y = 6x^2
				</me>
			</p>

			<solution>

				<p>
					This differential equation is first order and separable since 
					<md>
						<mrow>	x\frac{dy}{dx} + 10x^2y	=\amp\ 6x^2										</mrow>
						<mrow>			\frac{dy}{dx}	=\amp\ \frac{6x^2}{x}\left(6x^2 - 10x^2y\right)	</mrow>
						<mrow>			\frac{dy}{dx}	=\amp\ 6x - 10xy = (2x)(3 - 5y)					</mrow>
					</md>
					Therefore, we can apply the separation of variables method.
				</p>

				<p>
					<em>Note, the boxed expressions below are where we combined constants.</em>
				</p>

				<p>
					<sidebyside widths="36% 64%" valigns="middle middle">
						
						<p>
							Separate <m>\rightarrow</m>
						</p>

						<p>
							<m> \ds \qquad\frac{1}{3 - 5y}dy = 2x\ dx </m>
						</p>

					</sidebyside>
				</p>

				<p>
					<sidebyside widths="36% 64%" valigns="top middle">
						
						<p>
							Integrate <m>\rightarrow</m>
						</p>

						<p>
						<md>
							<mrow>
								\int \frac{1}{3 - 5y}dy	=\amp\ \int 2x\ dx \quad
								\left(
								\begin{array}{c}
									u = 3-5y,\\ 
									du = -5dx
								\end{array}
								\right)
							</mrow>
							<mrow>	-\frac{1}{5}\ln|3 - 5y|	=\amp\ x^2 + c_1	</mrow>			
						</md>
					</p>

					</sidebyside>
				</p>

				<p>

					<sidebyside widths="36% 64%" valigns="top top">
						
						<p>
							Isolate <m>\rightarrow</m>
						</p>

						<p>
							<md>
								<mrow>	\ln|3 - 5y|	=\amp\ -5x^2 - 5c_1													</mrow>
								<mrow>	|3 - 5y|	=\amp\ e^{-5x^2 - 5c_1}												</mrow>
								<mrow>		3 - 5y	=\amp\ \pm e^{-5x^2 - 5c_1}											</mrow>
								<mrow>		3 - 5y	=\amp\ \boxed{\pm e^{-5c_1}}\ e^{-5x^2}								</mrow>
								<mrow>			5y	=\amp\ c_2 e^{-5x^2} + 3	\qquad \left(c_2 = \pm e^{-5c_1}\right)	</mrow>
								<mrow>			y	=\amp\ \boxed{\frac{c_2}{5}}\ e^{-5x^2} + \frac35					</mrow>
							</md>
						</p>

					</sidebyside>

				</p>

				<p>

					<sidebyside widths="36% 64%" valigns="middle middle">
						
						<p>
							General Solution <m>\rightarrow</m>
						</p>

						<p>
							<md>
								<mrow>	y = ce^{-5x^2} + \frac35	\qquad \left(c = \frac{c_2}{5}\right)	</mrow>.
							</md>.
						</p>

					</sidebyside>

				</p>

				<p>
					The absolute value in the solution came from the <m>y</m> integral, which was later replaced by <m>\pm</m>. The <m>\pm</m> was combined into <m>c_2</m> since changing the sign of a constant doesn't change the fact that it is a constant.
				</p>

			</solution>
		
		</example>

		<p>
			The separation of variables method is a flexible and powerful tool for solving a wide range of differential equations, including nonlinear ones. As you've seen, the method is systematic: separate, integrate, and isolate. While the mechanics of the method are straightforward, the complexity often lies in the algebraic manipulation and integration.
		</p>

